From: Museum Security Network Mailing list <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Subject: [MSN] Van Mieris theft. Comment. The value of an
	unappreciated	artwork increases immeasurably once it is stolen,	writes
	Simon Caterson.
To: <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <010701c7af63$a43b6ed0$ecb24c70$@org>
Content-Type: text/plain;	charset="us-ascii"

Really love your work, darling
The value of an unappreciated artwork increases immeasurably once it is
stolen, writes Simon Caterson
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
----
 
June 16, 2007 

THE most famous exhibit at the Art Gallery of NSW reminds me of Joni
Mitchell, who sang of how you don't know what you've got 'til it's gone. The
theft of A Cavalier (Self-Portrait) has catapulted a hitherto obscure,
albeit saleable, painting to a prominence it never had when it was on
display.
That such an unheralded picture, painted by 17th-century Dutch artist Frans
van Mieris I, could arouse widespread public interest by suddenly
disappearing is nothing new, since this is one of the recurring ironies in
the long and colourful history of art theft. 

The international police agency Interpol ranks art theft as the third most
lucrative form of illicit international trade after drugs and arms. Works of
art, like drugs and arms, are valuable and portable, and their appeal knows
no borders. Art is also relatively accessible. 

Theft can do wonders for a painting's reputation. We are used to the Mona
Lisa being referred to as the most famous painting in the world, but that
status was attained only after it was stolen in August 1911. The theft of
the Mona Lisa was not noticed for 24 hours, but the news quickly travelled
across the world. While more than 60 detectives scoured Paris, the absent
painting in the popular imagination was transformed into the cultural symbol
we know today. 

As Darian Leader writes in Stealing the Mona Lisa: "Crowds gathered at the
Louvre to gaze at the empty space where the picture had once hung. Many of
these excited spectators, it turned out, had never been to the Louvre or,
indeed, seen the picture before." 

When he was caught two years later, the culprit, an Italian carpenter named
Vincenzo Peruggia, claimed to be a liberator rather than a thief. He
declared that the painting rightfully belonged in Italy, conveniently
ignoring that Leonardo da Vinci had happily sold it to the king of France
400 years earlier. 

Also claiming a higher motive than monetary gain was the mysterious thief or
thieves who perpetrated the most famous art theft in Australian history, at
least until now. 

In August 1986, Picasso's Weeping Woman disappeared from the National
Gallery of Victoria in Melbourne. In its place on the wall was a card with
the letters ACT written on it. Staff assumed the painting had been lent to
the national capital. In fact the acronym stood for Australian Cultural
Terrorists, which announced it had kidnapped the painting in return for
increased state government support for local artists. 

In his memoir The Bright Shapes and the True Names, Patrick McCaughey,
director of the NGV at the time, says he was mistaken in his assumption that
the level of after-hours security was adequate: "I learned later, however,
that the guards did not turn on the lights in the galleries but moved
through the huge building with a flashlight. In Roy Ground's echoing spaces
you could have hidden an elephant and evaded such a level of detection." 

Stolen art is sometimes not recovered for generations, if at all, and two
decades after the theft, McCaughey still has no idea who perpetrated the
theft, though he suspects it was an inside job, the likeliest scenario in
such cases, according to the experts. 

At least the Weeping Woman was returned unharmed by someone who evidently
knew how to take care of it. One of the biggest art thefts in history also
proved to be among the most destructive. During a six-year period from 1995,
French waiter Stephane Breitweiser, with the assistance of his girlfriend,
stole 239 works from 172 European galleries, including 60 old masters. When
his mother discovered the priceless haul, she cut up most of the artworks or
dumped them in a canal. 

Art theft often overlaps, unwittingly or not, with other crimes such as
forgery and fraud. In 2004, artist John Opit claimed that a burglar had
stolen art valued at $67 million from his home in Limpinwood, near the
NSW-Queensland border. Most valuable of all, Opit said, was a Cezanne
portrait worth $50 million. The police and art experts disagreed, and the
painting, which was scientifically tested after it was recovered from a
garage on the Gold Coast, was generally dismissed as a fake. 

The Opit theft may have been the real theft of fake French impressionist
art, but the reverse occurred in 1992, when Boston ophthalmologist Steven
Cooperman reported that two of his paintings, a Monet and a Pissarro, had
been stolen even though the alarm at his home had not gone off and there
were no signs of forced entry. Despite this, Cooperman successfully sued his
disbelieving insurers for $US17.5 million. Five years later, the FBI
secretly recorded incriminating phone calls in which Cooperman urged his
lawyer to chop up the paintings to remove traces of the scam. 

Theft on a mass scale is called looting and that goes back to the tomb
raiders who went to work not long after the ancient mausoleums were built.
Antiquities and art have been regularly stolen ever since. 

The biggest looters in modern history were Napoleon Bonaparte, Adolf Hitler
and Joseph Stalin. The Nazi plundering of Europe's art treasures continues
to have repercussions, as the Queensland Art Gallery discovered when a claim
was made in 2000 that a 15th-century German portrait of the Virgin and Child
it purchased in 1980 had rightfully belonged to Oscar Bondy, a Jewish art
connoisseur from Vienna whose collection had been confiscated by the Nazis
in 1939. After an extensive inquiry, that claim was proved true. 

The theft last weekend of A Cavalier puts the picture in impressive company.
The catalogue of lost art rivals all others, according to Simon Houpt in his
history of art theft, The Museum of the Missing. The immense gallery of
stolen art "would hold perhaps 150 Rembrandts and 500 Picassos. You could
stroll through the Renaissance galleries to admire Raphaels and Titians, da
Vincis and Durers, Rubenses and Caravaggios." One thing is certain. If A
Cavalier is recovered, we'll never look at it in the same way. 

Writer Simon Caterson is based in Melbourne.

http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/




