Surprise after collection check

An inventory of the Vestlandske Museum of Industrial Art in Bergen resulted
in a shocking discrepancy in the size of their collection.
"There is no doubt that we were surprised," museum director Jorunn Haakestad
told newspaper Bergens Tidende, after the process last year registered all
collection items in a computer database.

The museum believed they had between 20,000-25,000 objects at the facility,
but there are between 33,000-35,000.

"I think that the registration of collections at most other museums in
Norway would provide the same kind of surprise we got," Haakestad said.

At the same time Haakestad confirmed that any possibly dishonest employees
at the museum could have had easy and unchecked access to valuable items,
and that some kinds of theft could have gone undetected for many years.

Earlier this week the newspaper revealed that a large number of important
letter from the University Library collection of former Prime Minister Johan
Ludwig Mowinckel's documents had been stolen. 

http://www.aftenposten.no/english/local/article1838156.ece



